<subsection xml:id="subsec-surface-area-of-prisms" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Surface Area of Prisms</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.7 Surface Area
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <ul>
            <li>Determine the surface area of prisms, pyramids, cones, frustums and spheres</li>
            <li>Explore the use of the surface area and volume of solids in real-life situations</li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <p>
        The <term>surface area</term> of a solid is the total area of all its outer faces.
        It tells us how much material is needed to cover or construct a solid object.
    </p>
    <p>
        In this section, we begin with cubes and cuboids, then extend the idea to other prisms.
    </p>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-surface-area-of-cubes-and-cuboids">
        <title>Surface Area of Cubes and Cuboids</title>
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>2</m> or <m>3</m> students.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <term>Materials Needed:</term>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Solids made of cardboard or plastic (cube, rectangular prism, cylinder, cone, pyramid, sphere)
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Grid/graph paper or plain paper
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Scissors, rulers, tape, glue and String (for measuring curved edges like the circumference of a circle)
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Pre-made nets of solids (optional)
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
                    <p>
                        <term>Instructions:</term>
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>Choose one solid object (e.g., cube, cone, cylinder).</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>Create a net for the chosen object (either by unfolding a model or using drawn net templates).</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>Trace the faces onto grid paper or measure them using a ruler or string.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>Calculate the area of each face.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>Add up all face areas.</p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                    <image width="65%">
                        <latex-image label="cube-net-surface-area">
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw (0,0) rectangle (4,4);
                                \draw (4,0) rectangle (8,4);
                                \draw (-4,0) rectangle (0,4);
                                \draw (0,4) rectangle (4,8);
                                \draw (0,-4) rectangle (4,0);
                                \draw (0,-8) rectangle (4,-4);

                                \node at (2,2) {8 cm};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </sidebyside>
            </statement>
        </activity>

        <insight>
            <p>
                A <term>cube</term> has <m>6</m> identical square faces.
                <me>
                    \text{Surface Area of a Cube} = 6s^2
                </me>
                where <m>s</m> = side length of the cube.
            </p>

            <p>
                A <term>cuboid</term> (rectangular prism) has 6 rectangular faces.
                <me>
                    \text{Surface Area of a Cuboid} = 2(lw + lh + wh)
                </me>
            </p>

            <p>
                where <m>l</m> = length, <m>w</m> = width, <m>h</m> = height.
            </p>
        </insight>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Work out the surface area of a cube whose side is 8 cm.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The area of one face of the cube is:
                    <me>
                        S.A = 6s^2
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        = 6(8^2)
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        = 6(64)
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        = 384 \text{ cm}^2
                    </me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the surface area of a rectangular prism measuring <m>8 \text{cm}</m> by <m>3 \text{cm}</m> by <m>14 \text{cm}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The surface area of the rectangular prism is calculated using the formula:
                    <me>
                        S.A = 2(lw + lh + wh)
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        = 2(8 \times 3 + 8 \times 14 + 3 \times 14)
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        = 2(24 + 112 + 42)
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        = 2(178)
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        = 356 \text{ cm}^2
                    </me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-surface-area-of-triangular-prisms">
        <title>Surface Area of Triangular Prisms</title>
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangular prism has two identical triangular bases and three rectangular faces.
                </p>

                <sidebyside widths="45% 45%">
                    <image width="60%">
                        <latex-image label="triangular-prism-solid">
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \coordinate (A) at (0,0,0);
                                \coordinate (B) at (3,0,0);
                                \coordinate (C) at (1.5,2,0);
                                \coordinate (D) at (0,0,3);
                                \coordinate (E) at (3,0,3);
                                \coordinate (F) at (1.5,2,3);

                                \draw (A)--(B)--(C)--cycle;
                                \draw (D)--(E)--(F)--cycle;
                                \draw (A)--(D);
                                \draw (B)--(E);
                                \draw (C)--(F);
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>

                    <image width="60%">
                        <latex-image label="triangular-prism-net">
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw (0,0) rectangle (8,4);
                                \draw (0,4) -- (4,7) -- (8,4);
                                \draw (0,0) -- (4,-3) -- (8,0);
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </sidebyside>

                <ol>
                    <li>Find the area of one triangular base.</li>
                    <li>Multiply by 2 for both bases.</li>
                    <li>Find the perimeter of the triangle.</li>
                    <li>Multiply the perimeter by the prism length to get the lateral area.</li>
                    <li>Add all areas together.</li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
        </activity>
        <insight>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \text{Surface Area of a Prism} = 2(\text{Area of Base}) + (\text{Perimeter of Base} \times \text{Length})
                </me>
            </p>
        </insight>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the surface area of a triangular prism with base <m>8 \text{cm}</m>, triangle height <m>3 \text{cm}</m>, and length <m>12 \text{cm}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The area of one triangular base is:
                    <me>
                        \text{Area of triangle} = \frac{1}{2} \times 8 \times 3 = 12
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        \text{Two bases} = 24
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        \text{Perimeter} = 8 + 5 + 5 = 18
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        \text{Lateral area} = 18 \times 12 = 216
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        \text{Total S.A} = 24 + 216 = 240 \text{ cm}^2
                    </me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>


        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangular prism has two identical triangular bases and three rectangular faces.
                </p>

                <sidebyside widths="45% 45%">
                    <image width="60%">
                        <latex-image label="triangular-prism-solidd">
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \coordinate (A) at (0,0,0);
                                \coordinate (B) at (3,0,0);
                                \coordinate (C) at (1.5,2,0);
                                \coordinate (D) at (0,0,3);
                                \coordinate (E) at (3,0,3);
                                \coordinate (F) at (1.5,2,3);

                                \draw (A)--(B)--(C)--cycle;
                                \draw (D)--(E)--(F)--cycle;
                                \draw (A)--(D);
                                \draw (B)--(E);
                                \draw (C)--(F);
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>

                    <image width="60%">
                        <latex-image label="triangular-prism-nett">
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw (0,0) rectangle (8,4);
                                \draw (0,4) -- (4,7) -- (8,4);
                                \draw (0,0) -- (4,-3) -- (8,0);
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </sidebyside>

                <ol>
                    <li>Find the area of one triangular base.</li>
                    <li>Multiply by <m>2</m> for both bases.</li>
                    <li>Find the perimeter of the triangle.</li>
                    <li>Multiply the perimeter by the prism length to get the lateral area.</li>
                    <li>Add all areas together.</li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
        </activity>

        <insight>
            <p>
                 The surface area of a prism can be calculated using the formula:
                <me>
                    \text{Surface Area of a Prism}
                    =
                    2(\text{Area of Base})
                    +
                    (\text{Perimeter of Base} \times \text{Length})
                </me>
            </p>
        </insight>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                Find the surface area of a triangular prism with base <m>8 \text{cm}</m>, triangle height <m>3 \text{cm}</m>, and length <m>12 \text{cm}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The area of one triangular base is:
                    <me>
                        \text{Area of triangle} = \frac{1}{2} \times 8 \times 3 = 12
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        \text{Two bases} = 24
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        \text{Perimeter} = 8 + 5 + 5 = 18
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        \text{Lateral area} = 18 \times 12 = 216
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        \text{Total S.A} = 24 + 216 = 240 \text{ cm}^2
                    </me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <exercises>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A cube has side length <m>9 \text{cm}</m>. Find its total surface area.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>486 \text{ cm}^2</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A rectangular box measures <m>12 \text{cm}</m> by <m>7 \text{cm}</m> by <m>5 \text{cm}</m>. Calculate its total surface area.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>382 \text{ cm}^2</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A cuboid-shaped water tank measures <m>4 \text{m}</m> by <m>3 \text{m}</m> by <m>2 \text{m}</m>. Only the four walls and the base are painted. Find the area painted.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>52 \text{ m}^2</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A triangular prism has a triangular base of base <m>10 \text{cm}</m> and height <m>6 \text{cm}</m>. The two equal sides of the triangle are <m>8 \text{cm}</m> each. The length of the prism is <m>15 \text{cm}</m>. Find its total surface area.
                    </p >
                </statement>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>240 \text{ cm}^2</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A cube-shaped metal box has side <m>1.5 \text{m}</m>. If metal sheets cost <m>Ksh. 2,000</m> per <m>\text{m}^2</m>, calculate the total cost of making the box.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>Ksh. 36,000</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A triangular tent is shaped like a triangular prism. The triangular cross-section has base <m>4 \text{m}</m> and height <m>3 \text{m}</m>. The slant sides are <m>5 \text{m}</m> each. The length of the tent is <m>6 \text{m}</m>. Find the total surface area of the tent canvas (including the two triangular ends).
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>132 \text{ m}^2</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
        </exercises>
    </subsubsection>

</subsection>